ameter space at the LHC. In particular, we find that\ncustodians, like b' modes, can be as light as ~1200 GeV i.e. a mass lying\npossibly in the potential reach of LHC.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 28 Jul 2008 14:29:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 30 Sep 2008 00:31:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-01-12"}
{"id":"0807.4462","submitter":"Rodolphe Sepulchre","authors":"Silvere Bonnabel and Rodolphe Sepulchre","title":"Riemannian Metric and Geometric Mean for Positive Semidefinite Matrices\n  of Fixed Rank","comments":"the present version is very close to the published one. It contains\n  some corrections with respect to the previous arxiv submssion","journal-ref":"SIAM. J. Matrix Anal. & Appl., Volume 31, Number 3, page\n  1055--1070 - August 2009","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC math.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper introduces a new metric and mean on the set of positive\nsemidefinite matrices of fixed-rank. The proposed metric is derived from a\nwell-chosen Riemannian quotient geometry that generalizes the reductive\ngeometry of the positive cone and the associated natural metric. The resulting\nRiemannian space has strong geometrical properties: it is geodesically\ncomplete, and the metric is invariant with respect to all transformations that\npreserve angles (orthogonal transformations, scalings, and pseudoinversion). A\nmeaningful approximation of the associated Riemannian distance is proposed,\nthat can be efficiently numerically computed via a simple algorithm based on\nSVD. The induced mean preserves the rank, possesses the most desirable\ncharacteristics of a geometric mean, and is easy to compute.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 28 Jul 2008 14:40:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 21 Oct 2009 07:15:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-21"}
